sudo — run a command with elevated capabilities after re-auth

SYNOPSIS
  sudo COMMAND [ARGS...]

DESCRIPTION
  Authenticates the current user against /etc/passwd. If the user is
  in the admin set (caps contain "*"), the requested command is
  spawned with caps={"*"}. Otherwise sudo refuses with "<user> is not
  in the admin group" and the audit log records the attempt.

  Admins are users created by `useradd --admin`. Limited users (the
  default) cannot escalate even if they know an admin's password — the
  identity check is on the calling user, not on the password they
  type.

  Every sudo invocation — success, denial or password failure — writes
  an entry to /var/log/audit.log.

EXAMPLES
  sudo useradd --admin alex            # only an admin can do this
  sudo passwd                          # change the current user's pw
  sudo svc start uid                   # bring up the GUI from the TTY

SEE ALSO
  useradd(1), passwd(1), security(5)
